10:T819,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Can solar installation be planned without shutting down our operations?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Often the work can be staged around operating hours and access requirements, but electrical tie-ins may require a planned interruption. The schedule should identify disruption risks before construction."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is an older commercial roof suitable for solar?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Roof structure, membrane condition, remaining service life, drainage and warranty requirements all need review. If major roof work is approaching, coordinating both projects may reduce future removal costs."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What electricity information is needed for a commercial assessment?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Twelve months of bills are a useful start. Interval data, demand charges, operating schedules, planned equipment and information about multiple meters can make the analysis more representative."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can one proposal cover several buildings or utility meters?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, but each building and meter may have different loads, roof conditions and interconnection constraints. A portfolio review should show which sites offer the strongest practical fit."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How is commercial solar performance monitored?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Monitoring can show system production, equipment status and historical trends. Reporting needs should be discussed early if facilities, finance or sustainability teams require shared access or portfolio-level views."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Are commercial tax incentives or grants guaranteed?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Programs, eligibility and tax treatment can change and depend on the organization and project. Current official rules and a